  "prompt": "How can I transfer from an international university to a US university as a US permanent resident?",
  "response": "Transferring from an international university to a US university as a US permanent resident involves several steps. Here\u2019s a general guide to help you navigate the process:\n\n1. **Research & Selection:**\n   - **Identify Programs:** Start by researching US universities and identifying those that offer the program you\u2019re interested in.\n   - **Check Transfer Policies:** Each university has its own policies regarding international transfers. Look for universities that are open to accepting international credits and read their specific requirements.\n\n2. **Review Academic Credentials:**\n   - **Evaluate Transfer Credits:** Understand how your current courses may transfer to the US institution. This might involve course syllabi and detailed descriptions for evaluation.\n   - **WES or Credential Evaluation:** Some universities require credential evaluation by third-party services like World Education Services (WES).\n\n3. **English Proficiency:**\n   - **TOEFL/IELTS:** Although you're a US permanent resident, if your instruction was in a non-English language, you might need to prove English proficiency unless exempted by the university.\n\n4. **Prepare Application Documents:**\n   - **Transcripts:** Request official transcripts from your current university. Make sure they are in English or are officially translated.\n   - **Personal Statement:** Write a compelling essay explaining your reasons for transferring and how the US university aligns with your academic and career goals.\n   - **Letters of Recommendation:** Obtain these from professors or academic advisors who can attest to your abilities and commitment.\n   - **Resume/CV:** Highlight your academic achievements, extracurricular activities, and any relevant experience.\n\n5. **Standardized Tests:**\n   - Depending on the program, you might need to submit standardized test scores (SAT, ACT, GRE). Check the specific requirements of each institution.\n\n6. **Submit Applications:**\n   - Apply directly to the universities you've chosen. Be mindful of deadlines and ensure all necessary documents are submitted.\n\n7. **Financial Considerations:**\n   - **Tuition and Financial Aid:** Explore in-state tuition benefits you might be eligible for as a US permanent resident, and investigate financial aid options.\n   - **Scholarships:** Look for scholarships available to transfer students.\n\n8. **Visa and Immigration:**\n   - As a US permanent resident, you won\u2019t need a student visa, but ensure your residency status is up-to-date and complies with immigration regulations.\n\n9. **After Acceptance:**\n   - **Transfer Orientation:** Attend any orientation sessions for transfer students which will help you integrate into the new academic environment.\n   - **Advising and Registration:** Meet with academic advisors to discuss your class schedule and degree plan to ensure timely graduation.\n\n10. **Stay Informed:**\n   - Keep in touch with both your current and prospective institutions to ensure a smooth transition.\n\nIt\u2019s important to start this process early, as transferring credits and applications can be time-consuming. Always directly communicate with the admissions office of your intended universities to clarify specific requirements and guidelines.",
